<h1 class="hero-h">B2B content marketing playbook <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">for the post-AI-Overview era.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">The B2B content playbook of 2022 — write helpful, optimize for keywords, hope for SEO traffic — is broken in 2026. AI Overviews have collapsed mid-funnel traffic; generic content is being penalized; the distinctive operator-led content is winning. Here's what to actually do.</p>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
<div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;font-size:0.78rem;color:#8FAF8F;">
<div>By <a href="/about" style="color:#F0FFF0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Bill Colbert</a> · <span style="color:#4A6A4A;">Founder, Treetop Growth Strategy</span></div>
<div style="color:#4A6A4A;">Published May 2026 · <a href="/content-library" style="color:#8FAF8F;text-decoration:none;">More from the library</a></div>
</div>
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The shift</span><h2 class="h2">What changed in 18 months</h2><p class="body">Generic informational queries are now answered directly by AI Overviews and chat assistants — those clicks no longer come to your site. What does come: queries where the user wants a specific opinion, a specific framework, a specific operator's take.</p><p class="body">Implication: stop writing helpful generic content. Start writing distinctive operator-led content. The traffic shape changes — less volume, higher intent — and the buyer is more qualified.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The new content stack</span><h2 class="h2">What to actually publish</h2><h3 class="h3">1. Opinionated framework content</h3><p class="body">How-tos, frameworks, and methodologies with a specific point of view. Not "5 tips for X" but "Why X is the wrong question to ask, and what to ask instead." Becomes citable by AI assistants AND by other writers.</p><h3 class="h3">2. Operator-led narrative</h3><p class="body">Founder/exec/SME bylined posts grounded in specific recent experience. "Here is what we learned shipping X this quarter." Drives the trust that converts.</p><h3 class="h3">3. Customer stories with real numbers</h3><p class="body">Specific outcomes with specific situations. Composite case studies (clearly labeled) work fine when real names are sensitive.</p><h3 class="h3">4. Comparison and decision content</h3><p class="body">Buyer-stage content: "X vs Y," "when to choose X," "how much does X cost." High intent, high conversion.</p><h3 class="h3">5. Internal knowledge made external</h3><p class="body">If your team has an internal framework, document, or checklist that you use repeatedly — publish it. Distinctive by definition.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">What to stop publishing</span><h2 class="h2">Cut from the calendar</h2><ul class="ul"><li>Generic "What is X" articles competing on volume.</li><li>Listicles without a specific POV.</li><li>AI-generated content not anchored by a named author.</li><li>Roundups of other people's quotes without your own analysis.</li><li>Content written for SEO algorithms rather than for a specific reader.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Production model</span><h2 class="h2">Team shape for 2026</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>One editor / strategist</strong> who owns voice and POV.</li><li><strong>One operator-writer</strong> who can both report and write (or, alternatively, ghost for execs who can report but cannot write).</li><li><strong>AI tooling</strong> for research, briefs, drafts, and repurposing.</li><li><strong>One designer</strong> shared across content + brand + product marketing.</li><li><strong>Subject matter experts</strong> who contribute interviews, not full articles.</li></ul><p class="body">A 3-4 person content function with this shape can outproduce a 7-person 2022-era content team, with better quality, at lower cost.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">LLM-O</span><h2 class="h2">Optimizing to be cited by AI assistants</h2><ul class="ul"><li>Specific, sourced claims. AI Overviews cite confident, attributable assertions.</li><li>Clean URL structure, clear page titles, clean H2s.</li><li>FAQ blocks with structured Q&amp;A schema.</li><li>Author bios with credentials. Bylines matter.</li><li>Recency signals. Old pages get superseded.</li><li>Distinctive POV. Generic restatements of consensus are not citation-worthy.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Measurement</span><h2 class="h2">What to track in the new model</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Pipeline attribution by content piece.</strong> Which specific posts drive demos? Bet more on those.</li><li><strong>Time on page for high-intent content.</strong> If buyers spend 4+ minutes on your comparison pages, you are doing it right.</li><li><strong>Branded search volume.</strong> Your category awareness shows up here before anywhere else.</li><li><strong>Mentions in AI assistant answers.</strong> Hard to measure directly; track citations to your domain in public AI tool outputs.</li><li><strong>Subscriber growth (email, podcast, etc.).</strong> First-party audience is the long-term asset.</li></ul></div></section>

